                  <p>“He thought it might be one of the watchers, who are often seen in this length of coast-range, forms that look human to human eyes, but certainly are not human. They come from behind ridges to watch,” Jeffers wrote. “... He was not surprised when the figure turning toward him in the quiet twilight showed his own face. Then it melted and merged into the shadows beyond it.”</p><div class="adModule adModule--outer "><div id="CONCERT1" class="adModule--inner loaded" data-slug="Advertisement" data-disclaimer="Article continues below this ad" data-small="300" data-google-query-id="CImN_KK1pu8CFfsMBgAd56gPhA"><div id="google_ads_iframe_/36117602/hnp-sfgate.com/Local_2__container__" style="border: 0pt none; display: inline-block; width: 100%; height: auto;"><iframe frameborder="0" src="https://9c31b5aaba6a8617e576cbc48ec2f2a5.safeframe.googlesyndication.com/safeframe/1-0-37/html/container.html" id="google_ads_iframe_/36117602/hnp-sfgate.com/Local_2" title="3rd party ad content" name="" scrolling="no" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" width="0" height="0" data-is-safeframe="true" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" allow="conversion-measurement ‘src’" data-google-container-id="1d" style="border: 0px; vertical-align: bottom; min-width: 100%;" data-load-complete="true"></iframe></div></div></div>


          <!-- Missed: ad -->

                  <p>The next year, John Steinbeck, who grew up in Salinas, spoke of them in his short story “Flight.” In the tale, a teenage Mexican American boy kills a man and is forced to flee into the Santa Lucias. As his mother bids him farewell, she urges him to say his prayers, take care of his horse and “when thou comest to the high mountains, if thou seest any of the dark watching men, go not near to them nor try to speak to them.”</p>


